{{Infobox person | name = John "Smokey" Salmon | image = John Salmon (advertising executive).jpg | image_size = | caption = John "Smokey" Salmon | birth_name = John Michael Salmon | birth_date = 18 January 1931 | birth_place = [[Highgate]], London, England | death_date = {{death date and age|2017|4|7|1931|1|18|df=y}} | death_place = | death_cause = | restingplace = | nationality = British | residence = | education = | alma mater = | occupation = Advertising executive | title = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | known for = Creative director and later chairman, [[Collett Dickenson Pearce]] | boards = | salary = | networth = | spouse = [[Suzanne Jouvray]] (m.1953) | children = | parents = Thomas and Amelia Rose Salmon | relations = | website = }}
'''John Michael Salmon''', known as "Smokey" Salmon, (18 January 1931 – 7 April 2017) was an advertising executive who was known for his role at [[Collett Dickenson Pearce]] (CDP) and for "firing" the [[Ford Motor Company]] as a client after their [[public relations]] department attempted to interfere with his agency's creative process.
==Early life== John Salmon was born in [[Highgate]], London, on 18 January 1931 to Thomas and Amelia Rose Salmon. In 1953 he married a Frenchwoman, [[Suzanne Jouvray]], who later became a painter.<ref name=times>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/john-salmon-f903dmrjf Obituary: John Salmon.] ''The Times'', 25 April 2017. Retrieved 28 April 2017. {{subscription required}}</ref>
==Career== After service in the Royal Air Force, where Salmon became close friends with the writer [[Len Deighton]], he worked as a typographer and copywriter in advertising. He got a job at the American agency [[Doyle Dane Bernbach]] and in 1967 at [[Collett Dickenson Pearce]] (now [[Dentsu]]) in London where he rose from copywriter to creative director and later chairman, being known as "Smokey" Salmon.<ref name=times/><ref>[http://adfest100.co.uk/team/john-salmon/ John Salmon.] IPA Festival of British Advertising, 2017. Retrieved 28 April 2017.</ref> The agency has been described by [[Mark Whelan]] as being, in its heyday, "''[[Mad Men]]'' personified".<ref>[http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/lessons-cdp-legacy/998864 Lessons from the cdp legacy.] John Tylee, ''Campaign'', 16 April 2010. Retrieved 28 April 2017. {{subscription required}}</ref>
At CDP, Salmon worked with [[Charles Saatchi]] and [[Alan Parker]]. He mentored [[Alan Waldie]] who developed the [[Benson & Hedges]] "Gold" cigarette campaign. He recruited [[Omar Sharif]] to appear in advertising for [[Olympus Corporation|Olympus]] cameras and [[Alan Whicker]] to promote [[Barclaycard]].<ref name=times/> He developed memorable print advertising for the British Army and the Metropolitan Police.<ref>[http://www.moreaboutadvertising.com/2017/04/mike-everett-why-cdps-john-salmon-was-much-more-than-a-man-in-the-right-place-at-the-right-time/ why CDP’s John Salmon was much more than a man in the right place at the right time.] Mike Everett, ''More About Advertising'', 18 April 2017. Retrieved 28 April 2017.</ref> He "fired" the Ford Motor Company after their PR department attempted to interfere with his agency's creative process.<ref name=times/> When Frank Lowe, later [[Sir Frank Lowe]], left CDP to form [[Lowe Howard-Spink]], Salmon declined an invitation to join them.<ref>[http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/former-cdp-chairman-john-salmon-dies/1430378 Former CDP chairman John Salmon dies.] John Tylee, ''[[Campaign (magazine)|Campaign]]'', 12 April 2017. Retrieved 28 April 2017. {{subscription required}}</ref> He was described by Lowe as "one of the three greatest copywriters of the late 20th century" along with [[Tony Brignull]] and [[David Abbott (advertising)|David Abbott]].<ref name=times/> [[Jim Aitchison]] has written that as creative director of CDP, Salmon "presided over that agency's golden years of creativity".<ref name="Aitchison2012">{{cite book|author=Aitchison, Jim.|title=Cutting Edge Advertising: How to Create the World's Best Print for Brands in the 21st Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xAdNBXWOhJUC&pg=PT27|accessdate=|date=2012|edition=3rd|publisher=Pearson/Prentice Hall|location=Jurong, Singapore|isbn=978-0-13-341233-8|page=27}}</ref>
==Later life== After retirement in 1994, Salmon studied [[art history]] and obtained two degrees from the [[Open University]]. He and Suzanne indulged their interest in [[contemporary art]] and cookery. Salmon was an enthusiastic follower of American baseball. He died on 7 April 2017 and was survived by his wife and three children.<ref name=times/>
==Selected publications== *''CDP: Inside Collett Dickenson Pearce''. [[Batsford (publisher)|Batsford]], London, 2001. (With John Ritchie) {{ISBN|978-0713484038}}
